WEBVTT

00:00:02.240 --> 00:00:05.120
<v Teacher>What was <i>to know</i>?

00:00:05.120 --> 00:00:06.000
<v Student><b>Saber.</b>

00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:07.680
<v Teacher><b>Saber.</b> Good.

00:00:07.680 --> 00:00:11.280
<v Teacher>What would <i>I know</i> be, if it follows our rules?

00:00:11.280 --> 00:00:12.080
<v Student><b>Sabo.</b>

00:00:12.080 --> 00:00:13.120
<v Teacher>But it's not.

00:00:13.240 --> 00:00:14.440
<v Teacher>It's <b>sé</b>.

00:00:14.440 --> 00:00:15.800
<v Teacher>So it's an exception.

00:00:15.800 --> 00:00:16.920
<v Teacher><i>S-e</i>,

00:00:16.920 --> 00:00:26.200
<v Teacher>You might have heard <b>lo sé, lo sé</b> - literally <i>I know it</i>. Because <b>sé</b> by itself is a bit short, so you often hear people saying <b>lo sé, lo sé</b> - <i>I know it</i>, rather than <b>sé, sé, sé</b>.

00:00:26.740 --> 00:00:30.180
<v Teacher>So this is irregular, very irregular. <i>S-e</i>.


00:00:30.580 --> 00:00:33.700
<v Teacher>But the rest of the versions of <b>saber</b> are regular.

00:00:33.700 --> 00:00:38.260
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>he knows</i> or <i>she knows</i> or <i>it knows</i> or <i>you</i> (formal) <i>know</i>?

00:00:39.000 --> 00:00:40.120
<v Student><b>Sabe.</b>

00:00:40.120 --> 00:00:41.160
<v Teacher>Good.

00:00:41.160 --> 00:00:43.880
<v Teacher>So <i>I don't know</i>:

00:00:43.880 --> 00:00:44.680
<v Student><b>No sé.</b>

00:00:44.680 --> 00:00:45.480
<v Teacher><b>No sé.</b>

00:00:45.480 --> 00:00:50.600
<v Teacher>We said that <b>quiero</b> was <i>I want</i>, and <b>quiero</b> actually is an <i>-er</i> verb

00:00:50.460 --> 00:00:53.739
<v Teacher>so how would you say <i>I don't know what he wants</i>?

00:00:53.739 --> 00:00:55.020
<v Teacher>What is <i>what</i>?

00:00:56.140 --> 00:00:59.900
<v Student><b>Qué.</b> <b>No sé qué lo quiere.</b>

00:01:00.780 --> 00:01:02.140
<v Teacher>Why <b>lo</b>?

00:01:02.140 --> 00:01:02.940
<v Student><i>He</i>.

00:01:02.940 --> 00:01:08.380
<v Teacher>Firstly, you're not using the word for <i>he</i>, you're just saying <i>he wants</i> and that's contained in the verb.

00:01:09.020 --> 00:01:12.220
<v Teacher>But <b>lo</b> is not <i>he</i>, it's <i>him</i>. Not <i>he</i>.

00:01:12.040 --> 00:01:19.240
<v Teacher>We didn't learn yet the word for <i>he</i>. On purpose actually we haven't been learning these words so that we can just use the verb for now.

00:01:19.240 --> 00:01:20.040
<v Student>Ok.

00:01:20.040 --> 00:01:21.160
<v Teacher>So try again:

00:01:21.160 --> 00:01:23.320
<v Teacher><i>I don't know what he wants.</i>

00:01:24.300 --> 00:01:27.580
<v Student><b>No sé qué quiere.</b>

00:01:27.580 --> 00:01:27.820
<v Teacher>Good,

00:01:27.820 --> 00:01:29.980
<v Teacher>you must feel comfortable with two words becoming one.

00:01:30.380 --> 00:01:31.820
<v Teacher><i>I don't know what he wants</i>,

00:01:31.820 --> 00:01:33.740
<v Teacher><b>no sé qué quiere</b>.

00:01:33.740 --> 00:01:34.460
<v Teacher>Good.

00:01:34.460 --> 00:01:35.979
<v Teacher>The word for <i>he</i> is <b>él</b>,

00:01:35.979 --> 00:01:38.120
<v Teacher><b>él</b>. <i>E-l</i>.

00:01:38.120 --> 00:01:44.680
<v Teacher>If you want to be emphatic: <i>I don't know what HE wants</i>, or if you want to show or clarify who you're talking about, you can add that.

00:01:44.680 --> 00:01:45.640
<v Teacher>So how would you do that?

00:01:45.640 --> 00:01:47.320
<v Teacher><i>I don't know what he wants</i>:

00:01:48.100 --> 00:01:50.980
<v Student><b>No sé qué él quiere.</b>

00:01:50.980 --> 00:01:56.000
<v Teacher>Good. <b>No sé qué él quiere.</b> Or you can say <b>no sé qué quiere él</b>. You can do either; one sounds more emphatic than the other, and this is much better understood in live practice.

00:02:01.620 --> 00:02:06.180
<v Teacher>Because the emphasis isn't just in the sentence, it's with the hands and facial expression and tone of voice.

00:02:06.180 --> 00:02:08.500
<v Teacher>So it's something much better to get live.

00:02:08.500 --> 00:02:09.860
<v Teacher>No sé qué él quiere,

00:02:09.860 --> 00:02:11.700
<v Teacher>no sé qué quiere él.

00:02:11.820 --> 00:02:14.860
<v Teacher>The word for <i>she</i>, what is the word for <i>her</i> first?

00:02:14.860 --> 00:02:16.300
<v Teacher>We want to differentiate.

00:02:16.300 --> 00:02:20.140
<v Teacher>What is the word for <i>her</i>, like in <i>I want to see her</i>?

00:02:20.140 --> 00:02:23.580
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>I want to see, to view, her</i>?

00:02:24.940 --> 00:02:27.180
<v Student><b>Quiero verla.</b>

00:02:27.180 --> 00:02:27.500
<v Teacher>Good.

00:02:27.500 --> 00:02:28.940
<v Teacher><b>Quiero verla.</b>

00:02:28.940 --> 00:02:33.580
<v Teacher>But if you want to say she sees, it's not her, I

00:02:33.580 --> 00:02:36.060
<v Teacher><i>I want to see her</i>, it's <i>she</i>.

00:02:35.740 --> 00:02:38.140
<v Teacher>And the word for <i>she</i> is <b>ella</b>.

00:02:39.500 --> 00:02:41.820
<v Teacher>Now this is spelled <i>e-l-l-a</i>.

00:02:41.820 --> 00:02:44.860
<v Teacher>Double <i>l</i> in Spanish is pronounced /yuh/.

00:02:44.860 --> 00:02:45.820
<v Teacher><b>Ella</b>.

00:02:45.820 --> 00:02:46.620
<v Student><b>Ella.</b>

00:02:46.620 --> 00:02:51.340
<v Teacher>So if you want to say <i>she sees</i>, <i>to see</i> is <b>ver</b>, what type of verb is it? <i>-ar</i> verb, <i>-ir</i> verb, <i>-er</i> verb?

00:02:54.140 --> 00:02:54.860
<v Student><b>Ver.</b>

00:02:54.860 --> 00:02:56.220
<v Student>It's an <i>-er</i>.

00:02:56.379 --> 00:02:57.180
<v Teacher>An <i>-er</i> verb.

00:02:57.080 --> 00:02:58.520
<v Teacher>It seems too obvious to us.

00:02:58.520 --> 00:02:59.240
<v Student>Sorry

00:02:59.240 --> 00:03:01.320
<v Student>I thought you might be asking something more complicated.

00:03:01.640 --> 00:03:01.960
<v Teacher>No.

00:03:01.960 --> 00:03:02.920
<v Teacher>This is an <i>-er</i> verb.

00:03:02.920 --> 00:03:05.720
<v Teacher>So how do I say <i>she sees</i>?

00:03:05.720 --> 00:03:07.000
<v Student><b>Ella ve.</b>

00:03:08.439 --> 00:03:11.799
<v Teacher><b>Ella ve.</b> And if I know who I'm talking about I can just say <b>ve</b>.

00:03:11.799 --> 00:03:18.200
<v Teacher>Maybe when we are contrasting in the sentence we have a special desire to use these words.

00:03:17.800 --> 00:03:27.240
<v Teacher>When I say contrasting, I mean in the sense maybe I say <i>I want to invite him, but she doesn't want to invite him</i>.

00:03:27.140 --> 00:03:33.220
<v Teacher>So even if we know who I'm talking about, there I will probably use the word for <i>she</i> because I'm making that contrast.

00:03:33.220 --> 00:03:39.220
<v Teacher>Again these are things you just do very naturally without realizing it once you get practicing.

00:03:38.840 --> 00:03:42.600
<v Teacher>Also because your native language probably does the same thing as well.

00:03:42.600 --> 00:03:48.600
<v Teacher>Even if you don't have the choice whether or not to put <i>she</i> - like in English you always put it - you will stress it with your voice.

00:03:48.600 --> 00:03:51.320
<v Teacher><i>I don't want to invite him, but SHE does</i>.

00:03:51.100 --> 00:03:55.500
<v Teacher>So because you are stressing that with your voice in English, that's also going to carry over.

00:03:55.500 --> 00:04:01.820
<v Teacher>Many things are going to carry over that are positive language transfer that we might not necessarily address specifically.

00:04:01.340 --> 00:04:02.700
<v Teacher>So how would you say that?

00:04:02.700 --> 00:04:10.140
<v Teacher><i>I don't want to invite him, but she does want to invite him.</i>

00:04:10.140 --> 00:04:12.220
<v Teacher>So, <i>I don't want</i>:

00:04:13.340 --> 00:04:14.459
<v Student><b>No quiero.</b>

00:04:14.459 --> 00:04:16.859
<v Teacher><i>To invite him</i>:

00:04:17.019 --> 00:04:18.459
<v Student><b>Invitarlo.</b>

00:04:18.459 --> 00:04:18.859
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:18.859 --> 00:04:20.700
<v Teacher><b>No quiero invitarlo.</b>

00:04:20.700 --> 00:04:21.019
<v Teacher><i>But</i>:

00:04:22.060 --> 00:04:22.860
<v Student><b>Pero.</b>

00:04:22.860 --> 00:04:23.740
<v Teacher><b>Pero.</b>

00:04:24.060 --> 00:04:25.100
<v Teacher><i>She does</i>.

00:04:25.100 --> 00:04:27.660
<v Teacher>So actually we can just say <i>but she yes</i>.

00:04:27.660 --> 00:04:29.180
<v Teacher>What was the word for <i>yes</i>?

00:04:29.500 --> 00:04:30.060
<v Student><b>Sí.</b>

00:04:30.060 --> 00:04:30.380
<v Teacher><b>Sí.</b>

00:04:30.380 --> 00:04:31.980
<v Teacher>So we can just say <i>but she yes</i>.

00:04:31.980 --> 00:04:33.420
<v Teacher>How would you do that?

00:04:33.940 --> 00:04:35.460
<v Student><b>Pero ella sí.</b>

00:04:35.460 --> 00:04:36.419
<v Teacher>Good.

00:04:38.819 --> 00:04:41.940
<v Teacher>Or maybe I even use the word for <i>I</i> there to be emphatic.

00:04:42.099 --> 00:04:44.020
<v Teacher><b>Yo no quiero invitarlo.</b>

00:04:48.380 --> 00:04:52.220
<v Teacher>So we said that <b>salir</b> was <i>to leave</i> or <i>to go out</i>.

00:04:52.220 --> 00:04:56.460
<v Teacher>Now, <i>I leave</i> or <i>I go out</i> is <b>salgo</b>.

00:04:56.440 --> 00:05:08.040
<v Teacher>It's irregular, has the /g/ sound popping up. <b>Salgo</b>. But the rest of the versions are regular, so let's make them. How do you say <i>he goes out</i> or <i>he leaves</i>?

00:05:08.440 --> 00:05:09.080
<v Student><b>Sele</b>?

00:05:09.080 --> 00:05:12.360
<v Teacher>Again you're making some Turkish vowel harmony here.

00:05:12.680 --> 00:05:14.599
<v Student>Sorry, what's the <i>to</i>?

00:05:14.680 --> 00:05:15.639
<v Teacher><b>Salir.</b>

00:05:15.639 --> 00:05:17.720
<v Student>So it's <b>seli</b>-

00:05:17.720 --> 00:05:18.360
<v Student>No

00:05:18.360 --> 00:05:19.960
<v Teacher><b>Salir.</b>

00:05:20.000 --> 00:05:20.880
<v Student><b>Sale.</b>

00:05:20.880 --> 00:05:21.600
<v Teacher><b>Sale.</b>

00:05:21.600 --> 00:05:22.080
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:22.080 --> 00:05:23.840
<v Teacher>So that <b>sele</b> you put before

00:05:23.840 --> 00:05:25.680
<v Teacher>is because it just sounds better.

00:05:25.680 --> 00:05:29.040
<v Teacher>The mind has some kind of desire for this vowel harmony.

00:05:29.040 --> 00:05:30.640
<v Teacher>It's very interesting.

00:05:30.060 --> 00:05:30.780
<v Teacher><b>Sale.</b>

00:05:30.860 --> 00:05:32.139
<v Teacher>Now you can make me the rest.

00:05:32.139 --> 00:05:33.740
<v Teacher><i>They</i>, or <i>you</i> (plural),

00:05:33.740 --> 00:05:35.340
<v Teacher><i>you guys</i>:

00:05:35.340 --> 00:05:36.220
<v Student><b>Salen.</b>

00:05:36.220 --> 00:05:36.460
<v Teacher>Good.

00:05:36.460 --> 00:05:38.460
<v Teacher>And <i>you</i> (informal)?

00:05:38.580 --> 00:05:39.460
<v Student><b>Sales.</b>

00:05:39.460 --> 00:05:41.300
<v Teacher><b>Sales.</b> Good.

00:05:41.300 --> 00:05:46.580
<v Teacher>Now if you want to say <i>I'm going out to eat</i>, how is <i>I'm going out</i> again? So it should be <b>salo</b> but it was:

00:05:47.160 --> 00:05:49.960
<v Student><b>Sango</b>?

00:05:49.960 --> 00:05:50.680
<v Teacher><b>Salgo.</b>

00:05:50.680 --> 00:05:51.400
<v Student><b>Salgo.</b>

00:05:51.400 --> 00:05:52.040
<v Teacher><b>Salgo.</b>

00:05:52.120 --> 00:05:55.240
<v Teacher>So the irregularity is the same as the other ones that we saw:

00:05:55.240 --> 00:05:57.720
<v Teacher><b>tener</b>, <b>tengo</b>: <i>to have, I have</i>;

00:05:58.120 --> 00:06:01.160
<v Teacher><b>venir</b>, <b>vengo</b>: <i>to come, I come</i>;

00:06:01.160 --> 00:06:02.520
<v Teacher><b>salir</b>, <b>salgo</b>.

00:06:02.520 --> 00:06:05.480
<v Teacher>So how do you say <i>I'm going out to eat</i>?

00:06:05.480 --> 00:06:07.400
<v Student>I'm not sure of the word <i>out</i>.

00:06:07.400 --> 00:06:08.280
<v Teacher>This is the verb.

00:06:08.280 --> 00:06:10.360
<v Teacher>The verb is <i>to leave</i> or <i>to go out</i>.

00:06:10.360 --> 00:06:10.520
<v Student>Right.

00:06:10.760 --> 00:06:12.600
<v Teacher>So you don't need the word for <i>out</i>.

00:06:14.400 --> 00:06:16.640
<v Student>Salgo comer.

00:06:16.640 --> 00:06:18.480
<v Student>Salgo a comer.

00:06:18.480 --> 00:06:19.840
<v Teacher>Why did you think of the <b>a</b>?

00:06:19.840 --> 00:06:20.640
<v Teacher>I think you felt it.

00:06:20.720 --> 00:06:22.720
<v Teacher>You felt that sense of movement. Good.

00:06:22.720 --> 00:06:26.560
<v Teacher>So <b>salgo a comer</b>, it's a verb of movement. Good.

00:06:26.560 --> 00:06:29.040
<v Teacher><b>Voy a comer</b>, <i>I'm going to eat</i>.

00:06:29.040 --> 00:06:32.000
<v Teacher><b>Salgo a comer</b>, <i>I'm going out to eat</i>.

00:06:32.000 --> 00:06:33.440
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:06:33.440 --> 00:06:36.080
<v Teacher>What was <i>I have</i>?

00:06:36.900 --> 00:06:37.780
<v Student><b>Tengo.</b>

00:06:37.780 --> 00:06:38.740
<v Teacher><b>Tengo.</b>

00:06:38.740 --> 00:06:40.740
<v Teacher><i>I have it</i>:

00:06:40.740 --> 00:06:41.700
<v Student><b>Lo tengo.</b>

00:06:41.700 --> 00:06:42.660
<v Teacher><b>Lo tengo.</b>

00:06:42.660 --> 00:06:43.380
<v Teacher>Good.

00:06:43.380 --> 00:06:44.340
<v Teacher><i>I have them</i>:

00:06:45.960 --> 00:06:47.640
<v Student><b>Los tengo.</b>

00:06:47.640 --> 00:06:49.000
<v Teacher><b>Los tengo.</b>

00:06:49.000 --> 00:06:50.040
<v Teacher>Good.

00:06:50.040 --> 00:06:56.280
<v Teacher>If we add on <b>que</b> to <b>tengo</b>, and there's not really any comfortable translation for this,

00:06:55.860 --> 00:07:01.620
<v Teacher>but if we add on <b>que</b> we get <i>I have to</i>, in the sense of <i>must</i>, <i>have to</i>.

00:07:01.620 --> 00:07:06.500
<v Teacher>So for example if you say <b>tengo que comer</b> you get <i>I have to eat</i>.

00:07:06.340 --> 00:07:14.340
<v Teacher>So we change the meaning of <b>tengo</b>: like <i>have</i>, which is just possession, to <i>have to</i> by adding <b>que</b>.

00:07:14.100 --> 00:07:16.180
<v Teacher>Like I said there is no comfortable translation.

00:07:16.180 --> 00:07:18.100
<v Teacher><b>Que</b> is <i>what</i> or <i>that</i>,

00:07:18.100 --> 00:07:19.380
<v Teacher>it's also used as <i>that</i>.

00:07:19.380 --> 00:07:21.220
<v Teacher>We're going to use it like this later,

00:07:21.220 --> 00:07:24.500
<v Teacher>but again it's still very uncomfortable to translate.

00:07:24.500 --> 00:07:28.020
<v Teacher>So we will just say we add <b>que</b> and we get the meaning of <i>have to</i>.

00:07:28.320 --> 00:07:30.880
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>I have to do it</i>?

00:07:30.880 --> 00:07:32.160
<v Teacher>What was <i>to do</i>?

00:07:33.360 --> 00:07:35.120
<v Teacher>Begins with a silent <i>h</i>:

00:07:35.120 --> 00:07:35.680
<v Student><b>Hacer.</b>

00:07:35.840 --> 00:07:36.720
<v Teacher><b>Hacer.</b>

00:07:36.720 --> 00:07:38.960
<v Teacher>So <i>I have to do it</i>:

00:07:40.020 --> 00:07:42.100
<v Student><b>Tengo que hacer.</b> <b>Hacerlo.</b>

00:07:42.979 --> 00:07:43.540
<v Teacher>Good.

00:07:43.540 --> 00:07:46.259
<v Teacher><b>Tengo que hacerlo</b>, <b>lo tengo que hacer</b>,

00:07:46.259 --> 00:07:47.780
<v Teacher>you have the option.

00:07:47.539 --> 00:07:51.539
<v Teacher>So we've seen a few verbs with this <b>-go</b> business.

00:07:51.539 --> 00:07:53.699
<v Teacher><b>Vengo</b>, <i>I'm coming</i>;

00:07:53.699 --> 00:07:56.099
<v Teacher><b>tengo</b>, <i>I have</i>;

00:07:56.099 --> 00:07:57.780
<v Teacher><b>salgo</b>, <i>I leave</i>;

00:07:57.780 --> 00:08:00.099
<v Teacher>and we've seen that the <b>-go</b> just pops up

00:07:59.960 --> 00:08:04.440
<v Teacher>for the "I" version. It doesn't pop up for the other versions, this <i>g</i>.

00:08:04.440 --> 00:08:08.360
<v Teacher>So <b>tiene</b> for example is <i>he has</i>. <b>Tiene.</b>

00:08:08.360 --> 00:08:11.080
<v Teacher>How would you say <i>they have</i>?

00:08:11.840 --> 00:08:12.640
<v Student><b>Tienen.</b>

00:08:12.640 --> 00:08:13.440
<v Teacher><b>Tienen.</b>

00:08:13.440 --> 00:08:17.760
<v Teacher>And how would you say <i>you have</i>, speaking informally?

00:08:17.760 --> 00:08:18.640
<v Student><b>Tienes.</b>

00:08:18.640 --> 00:08:19.440
<v Teacher><b>Tienes.</b>

00:08:19.440 --> 00:08:19.760
<v Teacher>Good.

00:08:19.760 --> 00:08:24.400
<v Teacher>So if I give you the version for <i>he comes</i> it's <b>viene</b>.

00:08:24.440 --> 00:08:27.320
<v Teacher>So how would you say <i>you come</i>?

00:08:27.320 --> 00:08:28.280
<v Student>Informal?

00:08:28.280 --> 00:08:29.240
<v Teacher>Yes.

00:08:29.240 --> 00:08:29.960
<v Student><b>Vienes.</b>

00:08:30.120 --> 00:08:31.320
<v Teacher><b>Vienes.</b>

00:08:31.320 --> 00:08:33.560
<v Teacher>The word for <i>when</i> is <b>cuándo</b>.

00:08:33.560 --> 00:08:34.360
<v Teacher><b>Cuándo.</b>

00:08:34.360 --> 00:08:35.080
<v Student><b>Cuándo.</b>

00:08:35.080 --> 00:08:36.680
<v Teacher><i>When are you coming?</i>:

00:08:38.060 --> 00:08:39.659
<v Student>Informal, <b>vienes</b>.

00:08:39.659 --> 00:08:40.779
<v Teacher>It's the English that's confusing you.

00:08:40.779 --> 00:08:42.300
<v Student><b>¿Cuándo vienes?</b>

00:08:42.300 --> 00:08:47.500
<v Teacher>Exactly. So don't let that English <i>are you coming</i> confuse you.

00:08:47.500 --> 00:08:50.699
<v Teacher>There's a lot we're doing in English there that we don't need to worry about for Spanish.

00:08:50.699 --> 00:08:51.899
<v Teacher><b>¿Cuándo vienes?</b>

00:08:52.020 --> 00:08:54.180
<v Teacher><i>When are you coming to eat?</i>:

00:08:54.180 --> 00:08:56.000
<v Student><b>¿Cuándo vienes a comer?</b>

00:08:56.580 --> 00:08:57.780
<v Teacher><b>A comer</b>, very nice.

00:08:59.060 --> 00:09:00.340
<v Teacher><b>¿Cuándo vienes a comer?</b> <i>When are you coming to eat?</i>

00:09:00.340 --> 00:09:02.740
<v Teacher><b>Tiene</b>, what does <b>tiene</b> mean?

00:09:03.340 --> 00:09:03.980
<v Student><i>Have.</i>

00:09:03.980 --> 00:09:08.860
<v Teacher>But I need you to be more specific. I'm giving you more information than just <i>have</i>.

00:09:09.020 --> 00:09:10.220
<v Teacher><b>Tiene</b>:

00:09:11.440 --> 00:09:15.440
<v Student><i>He/it/she</i> or <i>formal you</i>.

00:09:15.760 --> 00:09:16.880
<v Teacher>Very good.

00:09:16.880 --> 00:09:18.160
<v Teacher><b>Ella tiene.</b>

00:09:18.160 --> 00:09:18.959
<v Student><b>Ella tiene.</b>

00:09:20.340 --> 00:09:21.540
<v Student><i>She has.</i>

00:09:21.540 --> 00:09:22.180
<v Teacher>Good.

00:09:22.180 --> 00:09:25.060
<v Teacher><b>Quiero saber qué tiene.</b>

00:09:25.060 --> 00:09:27.460
<v Student><i>I want to know what you have.</i>

00:09:27.460 --> 00:09:31.140
<v Teacher>What you have, or she, or it. Very good.

00:09:31.420 --> 00:09:41.500
<v Teacher>We said that a very interesting detail about <b>tener</b> is that you can also translate it as <i>-tain</i>, when this <i>-tain</i> forms part of another verb in English.

00:09:41.540 --> 00:09:46.740
<v Teacher>So <i>contain</i> becomes <b>contener</b>.

00:09:46.740 --> 00:09:50.500
<v Teacher>So how was <i>it has</i> or <i>she has</i>? <i>He has</i>?

00:09:52.100 --> 00:09:52.740
<v Student><b>Tiene.</b>

00:09:52.899 --> 00:09:54.420
<v Teacher>Yes.

00:09:54.420 --> 00:09:57.620
<v Teacher>We saw that it was <b>tiene</b>. We haven't looked at why yet, but we've seen that it's a little bit irregular.

00:09:57.620 --> 00:10:00.740
<v Teacher>In Spanish you can generalize this irregularity.

00:10:00.740 --> 00:10:02.500
<v Teacher>How is <i>I have</i>?

00:10:02.860 --> 00:10:03.660
<v Student><b>Tengo.</b>

00:10:03.660 --> 00:10:04.300
<v Teacher><b>Tengo.</b>

00:10:04.300 --> 00:10:06.860
<v Teacher><i>I obtain</i>:

00:10:06.860 --> 00:10:07.740
<v Student><b>Obtengo.</b>

00:10:07.899 --> 00:10:08.779
<v Teacher><b>Obtengo.</b>

00:10:08.779 --> 00:10:12.540
<v Teacher>Sounds rather formal in English, but in Spanish you might use it like <i>get</i>.

00:10:12.540 --> 00:10:13.820
<v Teacher><i>I obtain it</i>.

00:10:13.980 --> 00:10:15.180
<v Teacher><b>lo obtengo</b>.

00:10:15.180 --> 00:10:16.620
<v Teacher><i>I obtain it</i>.

00:10:16.980 --> 00:10:20.020
<v Teacher><i>To put</i> in Spanish is <b>poner</b>.

00:10:20.020 --> 00:10:21.140
<v Teacher><b>Poner</b>.

00:10:21.140 --> 00:10:21.780
<v Student><b>Poner.</b>

00:10:21.780 --> 00:10:22.580
<v Teacher>That means <i>to put</i>.

00:10:22.580 --> 00:10:26.100
<v Teacher>And <i>I put</i> you have the same business with this <i>g</i> popping up,

00:10:26.100 --> 00:10:27.380
<v Teacher>so how do you think it sounds,

00:10:27.380 --> 00:10:27.940
<v Teacher><i>I put</i>?

00:10:29.240 --> 00:10:30.199
<v Student><b>Pongo.</b>

00:10:30.199 --> 00:10:31.160
<v Teacher><b>Pongo.</b>

00:10:31.160 --> 00:10:41.160
<v Teacher>And <b>poner</b> is interesting like <b>tener</b>, because when we have <i>-pose</i> inside of a verb in English we can turn that <i>-pose</i> into <b>poner</b>, and we get the verb in Spanish.

00:10:41.520 --> 00:10:47.600
<v Teacher>So the example would be <i>compose</i> becomes <b>componer</b>.

00:10:47.600 --> 00:10:49.920
<v Teacher>So <i>to compose</i> is <b>componer</b>.

00:10:49.920 --> 00:10:52.400
<v Teacher>How would <i>to suppose</i> be?

00:10:53.460 --> 00:10:54.820
<v Student><b>Suposer.</b>

00:10:54.820 --> 00:10:57.460
<v Teacher>So <i>compose</i> is <b>componer</b>.

00:10:57.460 --> 00:11:01.220
<v Teacher><i>Suppose</i> is: <b>Suponer.</b>

00:11:01.220 --> 00:11:02.180
<v Teacher><b>Suponer.</b>

00:11:02.180 --> 00:11:04.820
<v Teacher>And how do you think you would say <i>I suppose</i>?

00:11:04.720 --> 00:11:09.280
<v Teacher>We want to generalize our irregularities in Spanish.

00:11:09.280 --> 00:11:10.720
<v Teacher>So how was <i>I put</i>?

00:11:10.720 --> 00:11:11.600
<v Teacher>How was that?

00:11:11.600 --> 00:11:13.840
<v Teacher><i>I put</i>: <b>Pongo.</b>

00:11:13.840 --> 00:11:14.480
<v Teacher><b>Pongo.</b>

00:11:15.120 --> 00:11:22.640
<v Teacher>So <b>suponer</b>, <i>to suppose</i>, becomes, for <i>I suppose</i>: <b>Supongo.</b>

00:11:22.640 --> 00:11:23.120
<v Teacher>Yeah.

00:11:23.120 --> 00:11:23.920
<v Teacher><b>Supongo.</b>

00:11:23.920 --> 00:11:27.200
<v Teacher>And you will hear <b>supongo que sí</b>, <i>I suppose that yes</i>.

00:11:27.200 --> 00:11:29.760
<v Teacher>I said that <b>que</b> can also mean <i>that</i>.

00:11:29.140 --> 00:11:31.140
<v Teacher><i>I suppose so</i>, we say in English.

00:11:31.140 --> 00:11:33.220
<v Teacher>In Spanish you say <i>I suppose that yes</i>.

00:11:33.220 --> 00:11:35.780
<v Teacher><b>Supongo que sí</b>. You will hear that.

00:11:35.780 --> 00:11:40.420
<v Teacher>So we had <b>componer</b>, <i>to compose</i>; <b>suponer</b>, <i>to suppose</i>. How would you say <i>to impose</i>?

00:11:40.420 --> 00:11:42.000
<v Student><b>Imponer.</b>

00:11:42.000 --> 00:11:44.000
<v Teacher><b>Imponer.</b> <i>To expose</i>:

00:11:44.000 --> 00:11:45.500
<v Student><b>Exponer.</b>

00:11:45.500 --> 00:11:47.000
<v Teacher><i>To oppose</i>:

00:11:47.000 --> 00:11:48.500
<v Student><b>Oponer.</b>

00:11:48.500 --> 00:11:50.000
<v Teacher>Yes. <i>I oppose it. I oppose it</i>:

00:11:57.880 --> 00:11:59.000
<v Student><b>Lo opongo.</b>

00:11:59.000 --> 00:12:00.519
<v Teacher><b>Lo opongo.</b>

00:12:00.519 --> 00:12:01.959
<v Teacher><i>I oppose it.</i>

00:12:01.959 --> 00:12:03.000
<v Teacher>Good.

00:12:03.000 --> 00:12:04.600
<v Teacher>And <i>I have</i>:

00:12:04.600 --> 00:12:05.240
<v Student><b>Tengo.</b>

00:12:05.399 --> 00:12:05.959
<v Teacher><b>Tengo.</b>

00:12:06.040 --> 00:12:09.240
<v Teacher>And we said we can add on <b>que</b> to get the meaning of <i>have to</i>.

00:12:09.720 --> 00:12:17.080
<v Teacher>So if you want to say <i>I have to see her</i>, how would you say <i>I have to see her</i>?

00:12:17.160 --> 00:12:19.960
<v Student><b>Tengo que verla.</b>

00:12:19.960 --> 00:12:20.600
<v Teacher>Good.

00:12:21.100 --> 00:12:24.380
<v Teacher>We can say <b>la tengo que ver</b> or <b>tengo que verla</b>.

00:12:24.380 --> 00:12:25.260
<v Teacher>Both are fine.

00:12:25.260 --> 00:12:27.100
<v Teacher>How would you say I must see her, I

00:12:27.100 --> 00:12:29.340
<v Teacher><i>I owe to see her</i>?

00:12:30.000 --> 00:12:31.520
<v Student><b>Debo verla.</b>

00:12:31.520 --> 00:12:32.560
<v Teacher><b>Debo verla.</b>

00:12:32.560 --> 00:12:34.880
<v Teacher>Or where else would you put that <b>la</b>?

00:12:34.880 --> 00:12:36.080
<v Student><b>La debo ver.</b>

00:12:36.160 --> 00:12:36.480
<v Teacher>Good.

00:12:36.480 --> 00:12:37.840
<v Teacher><b>La debo ver.</b>

00:12:37.840 --> 00:12:42.160
<v Teacher>The difference between <b>tengo que</b> and <b>debo</b> is exactly like English.

00:12:41.720 --> 00:12:45.320
<v Teacher>We use <i>must</i> when it's a bit more serious: <i>I must see her</i>.

00:12:45.560 --> 00:12:50.920
<v Teacher>And we say <i>have to</i> like an everyday kind of thing.

00:12:50.660 --> 00:12:53.700
<v Teacher>The way you use it in English and Spanish is exactly the same.

00:12:53.700 --> 00:12:59.780
<v Teacher>So <b>debo</b> is a little bit more severe, a little bit more serious, and <b>tener que</b>,

00:13:00.420 --> 00:13:04.180
<v Teacher><i>to have to</i> with <b>que</b>, is more everyday.

00:13:04.180 --> 00:13:05.860
<v Teacher><b>Tengo que comer ahora</b>.

00:13:05.860 --> 00:13:06.660
<v Teacher>What does that mean?

00:13:06.660 --> 00:13:08.660
<v Teacher><b>Tengo que comer ahora</b>:

00:13:08.660 --> 00:13:09.940
<v Student><i>I have to eat now.</i>

00:13:09.940 --> 00:13:10.259
<v Teacher>Good.

00:13:10.259 --> 00:13:12.180
<v Teacher><i>I have to eat now.</i>

00:13:12.200 --> 00:13:19.000
<v Teacher>What does it mean if I say <b>voy a intentar comer más tarde</b>?

00:13:19.000 --> 00:13:23.160
<v Teacher><b>Voy a intentar comer más tarde</b>:

00:13:23.720 --> 00:13:25.080
<v Student><b>Voy</b> is <i>I'm going</i>.

00:13:25.080 --> 00:13:25.720
<v Teacher>Yes.

00:13:25.880 --> 00:13:27.000
<v Student><b>Intentar</b>?

00:13:27.000 --> 00:13:28.920
<v Student>Can you say the whole sentence again?

00:13:33.780 --> 00:13:39.140
<v Student>It sounds odd because it sounds like <i>I'm going with the intention to eat later</i>.

00:13:39.140 --> 00:13:44.580
<v Teacher>Good, but it's not a noun. It's not the intention. It's not <b>la intención</b>,

00:13:44.000 --> 00:13:45.440
<v Teacher>it's <b>intentar</b>.

00:13:45.440 --> 00:13:50.240
<v Teacher>And when you hear that <i>-ar</i> on the end, you can suspect that it's a verb.

00:13:50.240 --> 00:13:51.840
<v Teacher>Most of the time it's going to be.

00:13:51.840 --> 00:13:54.080
<v Teacher>So you want <i>to</i> something.

00:13:54.080 --> 00:13:55.280
<v Teacher>a intentar:

00:13:56.400 --> 00:13:58.320
<v Student><i>I'm going to intend-</i>

00:13:58.320 --> 00:14:00.000
<v Teacher><i>I'm going to try.</i>

00:14:00.000 --> 00:14:00.720
<v Student>Ah.

00:14:00.720 --> 00:14:02.000
<v Teacher><i>I'm going to try</i>:

00:14:02.000 --> 00:14:06.080
<v Student><i>To eat later.</i>

00:14:06.080 --> 00:14:06.480
<v Teacher>Exactly.

00:14:06.480 --> 00:14:08.640
<v Teacher><i>I'm going to try to eat later.</i>

00:14:08.640 --> 00:14:09.600
<v Teacher>Good.

00:14:09.440 --> 00:14:18.480
<v Teacher>So let's make a very short recap on these useful verbs that tend to have verbs coming after them in this way, like <b>voy a</b>.

00:14:18.480 --> 00:14:21.520
<v Teacher>So we had <b>voy a</b>: <i>I'm going to</i>.

00:14:21.520 --> 00:14:22.080
<v Teacher><i>I can</i>?

00:14:23.480 --> 00:14:29.320
<v Teacher>It might help to know that the word <i>power</i> is related to this word in Spanish.

00:14:29.320 --> 00:14:33.400
<v Teacher>Of course when you <i>can</i>, when you're <i>able</i> to, you have the <i>power</i> to.

00:14:33.400 --> 00:14:35.640
<v Teacher>So it's related and it begins with <i>p</i>.

00:14:35.640 --> 00:14:37.960
<v Teacher><i>I can</i>:

00:14:37.320 --> 00:14:38.200
<v Student><b>Puedo.</b>

00:14:38.200 --> 00:14:39.880
<v Teacher><b>Puedo.</b> Good.

00:14:39.880 --> 00:14:41.480
<v Teacher><b>Voy a comer</b>:

00:14:41.480 --> 00:14:42.920
<v Teacher><i>I'm going to eat</i>.

00:14:42.920 --> 00:14:44.280
<v Teacher><b>Puedo comer</b> -

00:14:44.280 --> 00:14:45.880
<v Teacher>what does that mean?

00:14:46.120 --> 00:14:47.160
<v Student><i>I can eat.</i>

00:14:47.160 --> 00:14:48.040
<v Teacher>Yes.

00:14:48.360 --> 00:14:50.360
<v Teacher><b>Tengo que comer</b>:

00:14:51.040 --> 00:14:52.720
<v Student><i>I have to eat.</i>

00:14:52.720 --> 00:14:54.800
<v Teacher><b>Debo comer</b>:

00:14:54.800 --> 00:14:56.160
<v Student><i>I must eat.</i>

00:14:56.160 --> 00:14:56.880
<v Teacher><b>Quiero comer</b>:

00:14:58.620 --> 00:14:59.740
<v Student><i>I want to eat.</i>

00:14:59.740 --> 00:15:00.060
<v Teacher>Good.

00:15:00.060 --> 00:15:09.339
<v Teacher>So these verbs: <b>quiero</b>, <b>voy a</b>, <b>tengo que</b>, <b>puedo</b>, <b>debo</b>, they're very useful because we can just put the "to" form after.
